		<div class="lia-message-body-content">
			
                
                    <BLOCKQUOTE><TABLE border="1"><TBODY><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><TABLE border="1"><TBODY><TR><TD><BLOCKQUOTE><TABLE border="1"><TBODY><TR><TD>okay, here's a question for my readers: should I let other authors use "The Major" in their stories?  just looking for some advice on this matter<BR /><BR />Thanks for reading!<BR /><BR />~~The Original Major~~ </TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE><BR />No, they won't be able to capture his personality whoever the other author is.<BR /><BR />-Good Venson, "The Major is the Major, and nobody else!" </TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE><BR />"There really wasn't any one author in particular asking for him specifically, I was just thinking in the hypothetical event that someone did... anyways, I guess I'll just keep him to myself and keep writing chapters." -majorq10hero<BR /><BR />Actually, there is now an author asking for him. Or parts of him anyway. I want him for my book, which is aimed for publication. I have a militaristic group and for a while now it's needed someone to train the newbs. I've tried to have others fill the spot, but none of them were designed to be teachers, so I've been in a tough spot. I don't need The Major himself, he's your character, and I don't want to steal him. But, with your permission, I'd like to model this teacher off of The Major and name him/her Major Something-or-other. </TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE><BR />you are like the third person to ask <img class="emoticon emoticon-joking" id="joking" src="https://lego.i.lithium.com/lego/i/emoticons/joking.png" alt="Joking" title="Joking" />, ok, since you asked nicely, I'll tell you what: you may base your character on The Major, but you'll have to come up with your own name.  I'd much prefer to have readers who are inspired than readers who outright copy and steal.<BR /><BR />Anyways, that's the sum of it.  If you want to use the Major, the answer is no, but if you want to make your own character inspired by the Major, then the answer is yes (this applies to all readers)<BR /><BR />~~The Original Major~~
                
            
			
				<div style="width:98%; max-height:100px; overflow:hidden;" class="UserSignature lia-message-signature">
	~~The Original Major~~<BR />"The [^ is a lie!"
