                    <BLOCKQUOTE><TABLE border="1"><TBODY><TR><TD><BR />JAMMERS ON!!!  good.enough, axolc/XerxeseTortugas, dterne/AwesomeDino, ajrobot215, keegan8000 and IndianaBonesSulfrix9 ONLY!!!!!!!<BR /><BR />Grevesmad7 asked if he could use the Major and then did it anyways before I had responded, and I was going to say no.  His story is called "Last Stand," and he has already used the Major in ways that do not fit the character of the Major.  When I told him this, he just said "Well, CRUX TO YOU!!" and indicated he would continue.  I want to know if any of you think I should let him or make it clear that use of the Major is strictly prohibited.  Th last time I asked if I should let them use him, the answer was a firm NO, and I want to know if that's still true.<BR /><BR />JAMMERS OFF!!!!!! </TD></TR></TBODY></TABLE></BLOCKQUOTE><BR />JAMMERS ON SAME!!!<BR /><BR />,  Well, first, do you have any power to stop him?  Because if so, I would definitely try to stop him from using the Major as he has already done it contrary to your permission.  <BR />,  But if you do not have the power to stop him, I would make a bio that strictly defines the Major's character, background, habits, basically all the guidelines that you follow unconsciously when you write about him.  That way, you would at least have done all you could to keep the Major in character where ever he is.  <BR />,  If that still doesn't work, I would either completely ignore and forget the issue, or I would try to make it as unpleasant as I could for GravesMaddie whenever he used the Major in his story by quoting every chapter he was put in, and pointing out to Graves' readers that the Major is being used against your permission.<BR /><BR />JAMMERS OFF!!!<BR /><BR />-Good, "Maddie Graves, this is your Last Stand!"
                
            
			
